On one of the Sabbaths, Jesus was walking through the wheat fields with his disciples. And the disciples began to pluck some of the heads of wheat.
Then the Pharisees said to Him, "Look, why are they doing what is not lawful on the Sabbath according to the Law? Why do Your disciples do this?"
He replied, "Have you never read what David did? He and his men were hungry. They needed food.
That was when Abiathar was the high priest. David entered the house of God and ate the sacred showbread. Only the priests were allowed to eat it. David also gave some to his men.
So Jesus said to them, "The Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath.
Therefore the Son of Man is also Lord of the Sabbath.
Healing on Saturday
On another Sabbath, Jesus entered the synagogue, and there was a man there whose right hand was withered.
Some of the Pharisees were trying to find fault with Jesus. They were watching him closely. They wanted to see if he would heal the man on the Sabbath.
Jesus spoke to the man with the weak and withered hand. "Stand up in front of everyone," he said.
Then Jesus asked them, "What does the law say about this? Is it right to do good or to do evil on the Sabbath? To save a life or to kill?" But they remained silent.
Then Jesus looked at them and said, "How hard it is for you to understand and believe! It is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for someone who is rich to enter the kingdom of God."
Then the Pharisees went out and held a council with the Herodians against Jesus, how they might destroy Him. And many multitudes followed Him.
Jesus went with his disciples to the Sea of Galilee, and a large crowd from Galilee followed him.
The people heard of all that Jesus was doing. And many came to him from Judea, Jerusalem, Idumea, beyond the Jordan, and from Tyre and Sidon.
